<item>THROW DOWN THE GAUNTLET TO</item>
    </list>
    <list type="translations">
        <item xml:lang="zh">挑戰</item>
    </list>
<div type="definition">
<p>ADDRESS someone so as DEMAND to FIGHT WITH him, OR so as to DEMAND another COURAGEOUS REACTION.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. There is no obvious, common word for the concept of a challenge in classical Chinese. The only word I have found is zhì 致 when it refers to challenging an army to battle.</p>
        </div>
<div type="modern-chinese-criteria">
<p>挑戰 is the current word for a challenge of any kind, often also of a figurative kind.</p>
<p>叫陣 refers in a literary way to a literal challenge to battle directed at a military enemy.</p>
<p>求戰 refers in a literary and old-fashioned way to an effort at joining battle.</p>
<p>搦戰 nuòzhàn refers in a general way to a challenge to fight.</p>
<p>rough draft to BEGIN TO identify synonym group members for analysis, based on CL etc. 18.11.2003. CH ／</p>
        </div>
    </div>
